    <prp:abstract>SBW1 behind the Carina Nebula is a 5x104 Solar luminosity blue supergiant star located at a distance of 7 kpc.  It is surrounded by a remarkable set of three circumstellar rings;  a bright 5" radius ring and two off-plane rings which make it a virtual twin to SN 1987A.   It joins the handful of Galactic, massive,  post-main sequence stars surrounded by equatorial rings.  It is the clearest example of a triple ring system surrounding a blue supergiant. 

Band 7 ALMA observations are proposed to search for dust, molecular line emission, and to determine the mass and geometry of the neutral circumstellar disk and envelope of this massive post-main-sequence star.  These observations will measure the dust mass, radial velocity structure, and relative chemical abundances in this remarkable object.  

The results will shed light on the shaping of bipolar nebulae, asymmetric and axisymmetric mass ejection processes, and the circumstellar environments into which supernovae explode.</prp:abstract>
